solutions.content:
The idea is to maintain an array of the digits of N (actually only the first half of them) and increase them to form valid palindromes. Then we check if they are also a prime number.

The solution is arguably a bit convoluted because of all the low-level operations, but fast due to the fact that it doesn't rely on string operations.

I also added skipping even-digit palindromes after I read that they cannot be prime numbers ( -_-' ), which makes it even faster. 

````
class Solution {
    public int primePalindrome(int N) {
        if (N <= 2) return 2;
        if (N > 7 && N <= 11) return 11;

        int digitsCount = (int)Math.floor(Math.log10(N)) + 1; // number of digits of N
        if (digitsCount % 2 == 0) { N = (int)Math.pow(10, digitsCount); digitsCount++; } // skip even-digits palindromes
        int[] digits = new int[(digitsCount + 1) / 2]; // array of half the length of the number of digits
        // put the first half of the digits of N in the array
        int n = N, count = 0;
        while (n > 0) {
            if (++count > (digitsCount + 1) / 2) digits[digitsCount - count] = n % 10;
            n /= 10;
        }

        while (true) {
            // create a palindrome number based on the current digits and check if it's a prime
            int number = 0;
            for (int i = 0; i < digitsCount; i++) {
                int index = i < digits.length ? i : digitsCount - i - 1;
                number = number * 10 + digits[index];
            }
            if (number >= N && isPrime(number)) return number;

            // if not, increment the digits to generate the next valid palindrome
            boolean increment = true;
            for (int i = digits.length - 1; increment && i >= 0; i--) {
                if (i == 0) {
                    if ((digits[0] & 1) != 1) digits[0]++;
                    else if (digits[0] == 9) {
                        digitsCount += 2;
                        digits = new int[(digitsCount + 1) / 2];
                        digits[0] = 1;
                    } else {
                        digits[0] += 2;
                    }
                } else if (digits[i] == 9) {
                    digits[i] = 0;
                    increment = true;
                } else {
                    digits[i] += 1;
                    increment = false;
                }
            }
        }
    }

    private boolean isPrime(int n) {
        if (n == 1) return false;

        for (int i = 2; i <= Math.sqrt(n); i++) {
            if (n % i == 0) return false;
        }

        return true;
    }
}
````

