solutions.content:
# Brute Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
In brute force algorithm, we will iterate over all $i$ for $>=n$ && $<=2*10^8$ and check if that is prime and is palindrome or not. 
As soon as some i satisfies this equation, we will return the i.

Time complexity to find if n is prime or not $O(sqrt(n))$
Time complexity to find if n is palindrome or not $O(log(n))$

Overall this brute approach will take too much time complexity.

The optimized solution is deduced from one fact ------
All even length palindrome are divisble by 11.
And among all even length palindrome only 11 is prime. 
So now we have to worry about only odd length palindrome.
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Now, we make such algorithm which only checks for odd length palindrome and checks if that is prime or not.

This question also teaches us how to print all odd length palindrome efficiently.

Brute way would be to iterate over all possibilities and check if it is odd or not. 

The optimised solution to get only odd length palindrome is by making odd length palindrome.

Now we need to see that the answer lies between $[2,2*10^8]$. 
200000000 ---It is of length 9.
So the palindrome will be abcdedcba.
So, if we iterate over all abcde, we can make a corresponding palindrome and it will be a odd length too.
So by just iterating over abcde, i.e. 10^5. We can create all palindromes less than $2*10^8$ without iteration.

# Individual Complexity
- Time complexity: $O(100000)*[O(log(i)) + O(log(i)) + O(2*log(i)-1) + sqrt(x)]$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
where 
i will be $1<=i<=1e5$
I checked time complexities of the inbuilt functions also ans 
to_string(i)-------------------->$O(log(i))$
as there are $log(i)$ digits in integer $i$
reverse(s.begin(),s.end())-----> $O(log(i))$
stoi(s)-------------------------> $O(2*(log(i))-1)$ 
as the total length will $log(i)+log(i)-1$
isprime(x)---------------------> $O(sqrt(x))$

# Overall  Complexity
Time complexity: $O(100000)*[O(log(i)) + O(log(i)) + O(2*log(i)-1) + sqrt(x)]$

- Space complexity: $O(1)$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

