# Intuition
Just need to iterate only palindrome, so 
1st step: find the bigger nearest palindrome
2nd step: generate next palindrome
3rd step: check is this palindrome is prime, else repeat from 2nd step

# Implementation
- just hardcode for n <= 100
- Skip all even length palindrome, because its proved to be dividable by 11.


**1st Step:**
- Split n into left & right side, **example 435679328 (odd length of 9)**, split to **43567(left)** & **9328(right)**
- find the bigger nearest palindrome :
    **ignore the middle digit, which is 7**, and compare both side, for left side start from behind, for right side start from front:

compare 6 vs 9, if right side(9) is bigger, then increase the middle digit by 1 
and the **nearest parlindrom will be**
leftSide+1 concatenate reverse of leftSide.substring(0, leftSide.length-1) = 
(43567+1) concatenate reverse of 4356 =
43568 concatenate 6534 = **435686534**

**another example 754312609** , ignore the middle digit (1)
compare 3 vs 2, if left side(3) is bigger, 
then **the nearest parlindrom will be**
75431 + reverse of 7543 = **754313457**

**another example 961303782**, ignore the middle digit (0)
if both side are equal, compare the next digit
compare 1(left) vs 7(right), if rightSide bigger, increase middle digit and you get the nearest parlindrom, else if leftSide is bigger, just concat leftSide & reverse of leftSide, if they are same again, compare next next digit, and so on... 
**if all digits are same, then itself is palindrome.**


**2nd Step:**
Ok, now we can start from the nearest palindrome we've found in step 1.
Remember we split number into leftSide and rightSide? But now we only need to increment leftSide by 1 , then it is the next nearest palindrome!! so discard rightSide, its useless now.

**Using first example 435686534**, leftSide = 43568, 
while true iteration :

check if 435686534 is prime? 
yes -> return;
no -> 
    1. leftSide += 1 (43568 + 1 = 43569)
    2. form a new palindrome ( 435696534 )

end while

***Thats it!!***

**Note**: Example n = 990, 
leftSide = 99, palindrome = 99 concat 9, = 999
and when leftSide + 1 (=100)
since we concat leftSide + reverse of leftSide.substring(0, leftSide.length-1), 
= 100 concat 01 = 10001
that means we are always concatenating evenLength + oddLength OR oddLength + evenLength, so it is always equal to oddLength (skipping evenLength palindrome.)

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
- Space complexity: O(n)

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int primePalindrome(int n) {
        if(n <= 2) return 2;
        if(n <= 3) return 3;
        if(n <= 5) return 5;
        if(n <= 7) return 7;
        if(n <= 11) return 11;
        if(n <= 100) return 101;

        int len = getNumLength(n);
        if(len % 2 == 0) 
            n = (int)Math.pow(10, len++);   //  len increase 1 after this line

        int startLeftPart, palindrome = 0;
        String vLeftPart;     //  reverse of startLeftPart, so it becomes rightPart
        startLeftPart = findFirstPalindrome(n, len);

        while(true){
            String tempLeft = String.valueOf(startLeftPart);
            vLeftPart = strReverse(tempLeft.substring(0, tempLeft.length()-1));
            palindrome = Integer.parseInt(tempLeft + vLeftPart);
            if( isPrime(palindrome) ) return palindrome;

            startLeftPart++;
        }
    }

    int findFirstPalindrome(int n, int len){
        String leftPart = String.valueOf(n).substring( 0, ((len+1)/2) );
        String rightPart = String.valueOf(n).substring( ((len+1)/2), len);

        for(int i=0; i<rightPart.length(); ++i)
            if(leftPart.charAt(leftPart.length()-2-i) > rightPart.charAt(i))
                break;

            else if(leftPart.charAt(leftPart.length()-2-i) < rightPart.charAt(i)){
                leftPart = String.valueOf(Integer.parseInt(leftPart) + 1);
                break;
            }

        return Integer.parseInt(leftPart);
    }

    int getNumLength(int x){
        int length = 0;
        long temp = 1;
        while (temp <= x) {
            length++;
            temp *= 10;
        }
        return length;
    }

    String strReverse(String s){
        return new StringBuilder(s).reverse().toString();
    }

    boolean isPrime(int x){
        if (x < 2 || x % 2 == 0) return x == 2;
        for (int i = 3; i * i <= x; i += 2)
            if (x % i == 0) return false;
        return true;
    }
}
```

