![20211003_173451.jpg](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/0cadf77c-6d75-419d-83cb-0b445925a599_1683814982.5276306.jpeg)


# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
I figured just creating one list of all the prime-palindromes would reduce re-work, setup the list on solution creation, then all calls to PrimePalindrome(int n) just need to do one lookup in Log(n) time right? 
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Use Sieve of Eratosthenes and an Is Palindrome function to populate our memory cache of valid possible numbers. 

My sieveRange is actually incorrect as that's just the range of input N being checked, had to manually add the max possible num to the list as this solution timed out if I increased the range to include that prime palindrome. 

That misunderstanding of the range caused a lot of pain debugging. 

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
I should quit to become a sheep herder in the Alps. 

Sieve of Eratosthenes is typically considreed O(n log log n) so final for this solution is something like O(n * (Log(Log(n))) + Log(m)),
where m is size of the primePalindromes list. and that's ignoring the time of palindrome check, but I'm too damn dumb to get this exactly right.

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
Should be something like O(n + m), where n is the sieveRange (for the primes array in the SieveOfEratosthenes function) and m is the size of the primePalindromes

# Code
```
public class Solution
{
    // List to store prime palindromes
    List<int> primePalindromes = new List<int>();

    // The maximum number we will check for prime palindrome
    const int sieveRange = 10000000; 

    // Constructor: when a new solution object is created, it populates the primePalindromes list
    public Solution()
    {
        // Populate all primes in testing range
        SieveOfEratosthenes();
        // Max item that could be found within range
        // Honestly just found this in the editorial write up, times out if I try to calculate with sieve
        primePalindromes.Add(100030001);
    }

    // Method to find all prime numbers up to sieveRange using the Sieve of Eratosthenes algorithm
    private void SieveOfEratosthenes()
    {
        // Boolean array to mark prime and composite numbers
        bool[] primes = new bool[sieveRange];

        // Initially set all numbers as prime
        Array.Fill(primes, true);

        // 0 and 1 are not prime
        primes[0] = primes[1] = false;

        // Main loop to mark composites. If i is prime, then i*i to sieveRange are not prime.
        for (int i = 2; i * i < sieveRange; i++)
        {
            if (primes[i])
            {
                for (int j = i * i; j < sieveRange; j += i)
                {
                    primes[j] = false;
                }
            }
        }

        // Loop through all numbers and add the primes that are also palindrome to primePalindromes list
        for (int i = 2; i < sieveRange; i++)
        {
            if (primes[i] && IsPalindrome(i))
            {
                primePalindromes.Add(i);
            }
        }
    }

    // Method to check if a number is palindrome or not
    private bool IsPalindrome(int num)
    {
        // Single digit numbers are always palindrome
        if (num < 10) return true;

        // Reverse the number
        int reversed = 0;
        int original = num;

        while (num > 0)
        {
            int digit = num % 10;
            reversed = reversed * 10 + digit;
            num /= 10;
        }

        // If the reversed number is same as original, it is a palindrome
        return original == reversed;
    }

    public int PrimePalindrome(int n)
    {
        // Use binary search to find the index of the smallest prime palindrome >= n
        int idx = primePalindromes.BinarySearch(n);

        if (idx < 0)
        {
            // If the exact value is not found, BinarySearch returns the bitwise    complement of the index of the next larger element
            idx = ~idx;
        }     

        // Return the prime palindrome at the found index
        return primePalindromes[idx];
    }
}

```

