# Intuition
Some points to note:
- Far fewer numbers are palindrome than not
- Palindromes can easily be generated from their first half (for palindromes of odd length, including their middle digit)
- The numerical order of (odd length) palindromes is equal to the order of their first halves. Therefore, it is easy to iterate over all palindromes in ascending order by iterating over their first halves.

# Approach
`oddPalindrome` generates an odd-length palindrome from the integer representing its first half (inclunding middle digit) by adding the string representation and its reverse, excluding the duplicate middle digit. 
`IsPrime` is used to check whether the generated number is a prime number.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
Checking primeness: $$O(\sqrt{n})$$ 
Finding prime palindrome: Unknown, as palindromes can not be regarded as random integers and therefore, the density of prime palindromes is not equal to that of primes in general.

- Space complexity:
$$O(log(n))$$, the extra memory increases with the length of the result in decimal representation.

# Code
```
public class Solution {
    public int PrimePalindrome(int n) {
        string Reverse(string text) {
            char[] array = text.ToCharArray();
            Array.Reverse(array);
            return new String(array);
        }
        int oddPalindrome(int a) {
            return int.Parse(a.ToString() + Reverse(a.ToString()).Substring(1));
        }
        bool isPrime(int a) {
            if(a < 2 || a == 9)
                return false;
            if(a == 2 || a == 3 || a == 5 || a == 7)
                return true;
            int sqrt = (int)Math.Sqrt(a)+1;
            if(a%2 == 0)
                return false;
            for(int i = 3; i < sqrt; i+=2)
            {
                if(a%i==0)
                    return false;
            }
            return true;
        }

        if(n >= 8 && n <= 11) // The only numbers resulting in 11, the only palindrome prime with an even number of digtis
            return 11;

        int x = int.Parse(n.ToString().Substring(0,(n.ToString().Length + 1) / 2) );
        while(x < 100000) //some upper limit
        {
            int p = oddPalindrome(x);
            if(p >= n && isPrime(p))
                return p;
            x++;
        }
        return -1;
    }
}
```

