solutions.content:
According to Euclid's Theorem,
***If the GCD of two integers (a,b) is d, then there exists two integers x and y such that ax + by = d.***

If a,b,c... are the elements of the array we are calculating ax + by + cz...which gives hint that we have to use the above theorem.

Now in this problem the d is given to be 1, which means the GCD should be 1.
So instead of checking for all posiible subsets of the given array it is enough to check every pair (a,b).
***"Does the array contain two integers a and b such that ax + by = 1 for some integers x,y ?"***
Or the same question can be asked as
***"Does the array contain two co-prime integers?"***

But checking all pairs will have quadratic time complexity. We have to optimize it.

Now what happens if we calculate the GCD of all the integers in the array ?
If the array contains co-prime integers then the GCD of those two will become 1 and the GCD of 1 with the remaining n-2 integers will be 1 only.
But if the array does not contain coprime integers then the GCD of all the integers will be greater than 1.

So the question reduces to
***"Is the GCD of all the number in the array equal to 1?"***
```
class Solution {
public:
    bool isGoodArray(vector<int>& nums)
    {
        int GCD = nums[0];

        for (int i = 1; i < nums.size(); i++)
        {
            GCD = __gcd(GCD, nums[i]);
        }

        return GCD == 1;
    }
};
```

