consider ax + by = 1
Assuming integer solution exists then 

we can take out the common divisor of a and b. 
The gcf is the greatest common divisor of a and b.

therefor ax + by = gcf(a,b) * ( (a/gcf) * x + (b/gcf) * y ) = 1

since gcf divides a we can rewrite a as a = gcf * a1 .. where a1 is some integer
similarly b = gcf * b1.. where b1 is some integer

so ax + by = gcf * ( a1 * x + b1 * y ) = 1

dividing both sides by gcf we get

a1 * x + b1 * y = 1 / gcf

Now LHS is a integer because (a1, b1, x, y ) are all integer values. and LHS = RHS. Therefore 1/gcf should also be an integer. This is only possible when gcf = 1. For all other values 1/gcf will not be an integer.
Also if (x,y) integer solutions don't exist the condition won' t be valid.

Therefor ax + by = 1 only if gcf(a,b) = 1

For n variables as given in the question similar logic can be used to take out gcf( a, b, c , d .... ) common from LHS and we get gcf(a,b,c,d ... ) = 1 as the condition.

One must realise that the subarray simply means taking the 0 as the multiplicative coefficients for number not included.

