Since the GCD is an associative function, we have
* gcd(a<sub>0</sub>, a<sub>1</sub>,...,a<sub>n - 1</sub>) = gcd(a<sub>0</sub>, gcd(a<sub>1</sub>,...,a<sub>n-1</sub>) = gcd(gcd(a<sub>0</sub>, a<sub>1</sub>), gcd(a<sub>2</sub>,...,a<sub>n-1</sub>)) = ...

and so on, every possible combination is included. So we just have to iterate through `nums` until we find a gcd of `1`. In other world, if gcd(a<sub>0</sub>, a<sub>1</sub>,...,a<sub>n - 1</sub>) = 1, there exist a subsequence a<sub>i<sub>j</sub></sub> with #{a<sub>i<sub>0</sub></sub>,...,a<sub>i<sub>k</sub></sub>} = k, 1 <= k <= n, that give a gcd of `1.`

```
class Solution {

public:

    bool isGoodArray(vector<int>& nums) {
        if(nums.size() == 1 and nums[0] == 1) return true;
        int gcd = 0;
        for(int i = 0; i < nums.size(); ++i) {
            if(i == 0) gcd = nums[i];
            else {
                gcd = __gcd(gcd, nums[i]);
                if(gcd == 1) return true;
            }
        }
        return false;
    }
};
```

