solutions.content:
# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

An equation 
$$a_1x_1+a_2x_2+...a_kx_k=d$$

Has integer solutions $x_1\in \mathbb{Z}, x_2\in \mathbb{Z},...x_k\in\mathbb{Z}$ if and only if $d$ divides $gcd(a_1,a_2,...a_k)$.

Since here in this case $d=1$, then it is equivalent to asking is 
$$gcd(a_1,a_2,...a_k) = 1$$ 
(since only 1 divides 1).

Now, the gcd can only ever get smaller when you add more numbers to the set of numbers to analyze the gcd() of. I.e.

$$gcd(a_1,a_2,...a_{k-1}) \geq gcd(a_1,a_2,...a_k)$$

So, although the questions asks for if there are any *subsets* of the provided array that fulfil the above property, the easier thing to do actually is to just, take the gcd() of the entire array in a rolling-basis, and return true the moment that rolling gcd() is equal to 1.

We don't need to individually trial each possible subset, because of the property above that the gcd() only gets smaller with each element added. So, effectively, the gcd() of the whole array is the *minimum possible gcd* of the entire array. 

So, if even *that* doesn't get us down to 1, then the answer return should be false.


# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The time complexity of a gcd operations is O(log(min(a, b))), for some gcd(a,b) operation. Since we analyze the gcd across all elements in the vector, the time complexity is in the order of O(n logm), with m being the average 'magnitude' of the numbers of the array, of size n.

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
Constant space O(1)

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    bool isGoodArray(vector<int>& nums) {
        /* linear diophantine equations */

        if (nums.size() == 1) return (nums[0] == 1);

        int currgcd = nums[0];
        if (currgcd == 1) return true;

        for (int i=1;i<nums.size();i++){
            currgcd = __gcd(currgcd, nums[i]);
            if (currgcd == 1) return true;
        }

        return false;
    }
};
```

