solutions.content:
**Observations:**
(1) Boxes must be handled in order from left to right, this is a signal to use DP.
(2)  Since it is 10^5. DP must be 1-dimension, i.e, for every index `i` we need to find a single index `j` and apply `DP[i] = f(DP[j])` for some DP function `f`. 

Let `dp[i+1]` be the minimum cost (# of ships) to process all boxes from 0 to i and return to the storage. 

From observation (2), we need to find the best position `start` where we can load up all boxes from `start` to `i` and then go in a single voyage, then `dp[i+1] = dp[start] + something`.

To find `start`, we use **sliding window**. We slide `start` forward for 3 reasons:
1. limit # of boxes in 1 voyage
2. limit total weight in 1 voyage
3. No benefit to load the box at position `start` (i.e `dp[start] == dp[start+1]`), because the cost to keep the box on the ship is at most 1. (More explanation for Policy 3 at the end of the post).

More details in the code. 

```
class Solution {
    public int boxDelivering(int[][] A, int portsCount, int m1, int m2) {
        int n = A.length;

        boolean[] C = new boolean[n]; // consecutive ports are different or not
        for (int i = 0; i< n-1; i++){
            if (A[i][0] != A[i+1][0]) C[i] = true;
        }

        int[] dp = new int[n+1];
        int sum = 0; // total current weight on the ship
        int start = 0; // load all boxes from start to i in one voyage
        int diff = 0; // # different consecutive ports between start and i

        for (int i = 0; i< n; i++){
            if (i-start == m1) { // drop 1 box because of # boxes constraint
                sum-= A[start][1];
                if (C[start]) diff--;
                start++;
            }

            // Add box i, update current weight and diff
            sum+= A[i][1];
            if (i> 0 && C[i-1]) diff++;

            while (sum > m2){ // drop more boxex because of weight constraint
                sum-= A[start][1];
                if (C[start]) diff--;
                start++;
            }

            while(start < i && dp[start] == dp[start+1]){
                // drop more boxes if there is no point to carry them
                sum-= A[start][1];
                if (C[start]) diff--;
                start++;
            }

            dp[i+1] = diff+2 + dp[start];
        }
        return dp[n];
    }
}
```

Answer question `why we stop dropping when dp[start + 1] > dp[start]` by @cpcs:

In fact, every `j` from `start` onward (after applying 3 policies above) have the following properties:
(a) The cost to keep the box `j` on the ship is  0 if `A[j][0] = A[j+1][0]` (i.e. same ports), and is 1 if `A[j][0] != A[j+1][0]`.
(b) if `A[j][0] != A[j+1][0]` then  `dp[j + 2] >  dp[j+1]`.

This means that if we drop box j and save 1 cost thanks to Observation (a), we have to pay it back 1 step later if we continue to drop box j+1 thanks to Observation (b). Now you say "yay, if I drop j but don't drop j+1, then I save 1 cost". But indeed we already pay upfront 1 cost for nothing because we drop `start` some moment ago. So all in all, we never save cost by continuing dropping boxes after satisfying all 3 policies above. This is why we stop dropping when `dp[start + 1] > dp[start]`.

