#### Bruteforce (TLE)

The idea is that **dynamic programming** is needed because we want to know the best possible answer if we start a new delivery at every `i`. This gives us a good insight for **O(N^2) TLE** pseudocode solution:
```
vector<int> dp(n+1);
for (int i = n - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
	for (int j = i; j < n; j++) {
		if (/*we can take all the boxes within boxes[i,j] */) {
			dp[i] = min(dp[i], dp[j + 1] + /* number of different adjacent boxes in [i, j] */ + 1);
		}
	}
}
```

We wish to improve our solution *by eliminating the process of inner loop*. But, how do we know which `j` to pick for every `i`? This is where our **greedy** part of the solution come in.

---

#### Greedy Speedup (Accepted)

We need to observe two **greedy** factors we want to maximize to get our best answer:
1. We want to take as many boxes as possible per trip
2. We want to take as many of the same boxes as possible

This gives us the **two pointer** part of the problem, where each pointer figures our the starting point that matches their corresponding factor. An example is shown below to demonstrate the concept further:
```
I labeled boxes by letters for convenience

AAABBBCCCDDD[DD] <- cannot fit into one trip
---------+++
^         ^
^         only have enough room for 3 D boxes
^
for sure can take with current trip
```

We can observe that if we decide to try to fit a group of same boxes into a trip but there is not enough room: we can pick one of the following:
1. If we decide to take some boxes anyway, **take as much as we can** and whatever is left is the starting point of a new trip
2. We abandon that group of boxes, so **leave them alone** and they become the starting point of a new trip

Then we pick whichever one would give us the best answer. All we have to do now is update both pointers accordingly for the new starting point.

---

#### Number of Different Adjacent Boxes in Range

This information can be preprocessed in O(n) and calculated in O(1) afterwards. We will use **prefix sum**, which we will increase the current count by 1 if the current box is different from the last one.

One problem to watch out for is if the range corresponds to just a single box, then we will get `0` if we naively do the normal subtraction with prefix sum. I have created a new array called `pp` which corresponds to the first index of the range of a different boxes to the left. This way, we can subtract the count from different range of boxes instead of subtracting two of the same range.

---

**Time Complexity: O(N)**
**Space Complexity: O(N)**

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    int boxDelivering(vector<vector<int>> &boxes, int portsCount, int maxBoxes, int maxWeight) {
        int n = boxes.size();

        vector<int> p(n + 1), pp(n);
        for (int i = 0, prev = -1, prev2 = 0; i < n; i++) {
            p[i + 1] = p[i];
            if (boxes[i][0] != prev) {
                p[i + 1]++;
                prev = boxes[i][0];
                prev2 = i;
            }
            pp[i] = prev2;
        }

        vector<int> dp(n + 1);
        int weight = 0, k = 0;
        for (int l = n - 1, r1 = n - 1, r2 = n - 1; l >= 0; l--) {
            weight += boxes[l][1];
            k++;
            while (weight > maxWeight || k > maxBoxes) {
                weight -= boxes[r2][1];
                k--;
                r2--;
            }
            r1 = min(r1, r2);
            while (r1 > l && p[r2 + 1] - p[pp[r1]] == 1 && boxes[r1][0] == boxes[r2][0]) {
                r1--;
            }
            assert(r1 >= l);
            assert(r1 <= r2);
            dp[l] = min(p[r1 + 1] - p[pp[l]] + dp[r1 + 1], p[r2 + 1] - p[pp[l]] + dp[r2 + 1]) + 1;
        }
        return dp[0];
    }
};
```

