solutions.content:
Instead of trying to loop through every point that exists or every point that *might* exist we maintain the points in a two-layer HashMap. This lets us loop through ONLY the points which actually exist! We also can ignore all points except for one axis since there has to be a match on one of axis (in this case, X) in order to justify even checking the other axis.

There is no specific reason the Map has to be X-dominant, this function would work the same if we instead structured it around the Y-axis.

```
class DetectSquares {

    // Custom wrapper for Map<Integer, Map<Integer, Integer>>
	// Structured as Map<int x, Map<int y, int count>>
    private PointMap pm;

    public DetectSquares() {
        pm = new PointMap();
    }

    public void add(int[] point) {
        pm.add(point[0], point[1]);
    }

    public int count(int[] point) {
        int x1 = point[0];
        int y1 = point[1];
        int result = 0;
		//  Entries consist of all Y-axis positions and counts, for all points matching this X-axis position
        for (Map.Entry<Integer, Integer> p2 : pm.getPoints(x1)) {
            int y2 = p2.getKey();
            int count1 = p2.getValue();
            if (y1 == y2) {
                // Don't try to make squares with 0-length sides
                continue;
            }
            // No need to Math.abs() here - Doesn't really matter whether 
            // this is positive or negative since we use both values
            int distance = y2 - y1;
            // Need to check for squares in both directions
            int x2 = x1 + distance;
            int x3 = x1 - distance;
            // Calculate how many squares can be constructed
			// Both squares start with two known values - [x1,y1] provided by the function call
			// And [x1,y2] which started this loop
			// We then combine these by querying for counts of [x2,y1] and [x2,y2]
            result += count1 * pm.getCount(x2, y1) * pm.getCount(x2, y2);
			// And again - this time in the opposite direction, searching for [x3,y1] and [x3,y2]
            result += count1 * pm.getCount(x3, y1) * pm.getCount(x3, y2);
        }
        return result;
    }
}

// This class is just useful to isolate all the Map-traversal
// code rather than doing it all inline.
class PointMap {
	// Map<int x, Map<int y, int count>>
    private Map<Integer, Map<Integer, Integer>> points;

    public PointMap() {
        points = new HashMap<>();
    }

    public void add(int x, int y) {
        var yMap = points.get(x);
        if(yMap == null) {
            yMap = new HashMap<>();
        }
        yMap.put(y, yMap.getOrDefault(y, 0) +1);
        points.put(x, yMap);
    }

    public int getCount(int x, int y) {
        var yMap = points.get(x);
        if(yMap != null) {
            return yMap.getOrDefault(y, 0);
        }
        return 0;
    }

	// Get all counts for points along this point on the X axis, indexed by Y position
    public Set<Map.Entry<Integer, Integer>> getPoints(int x) {
        if(points.get(x) == null) {
            return new HashSet<>();
        }
        return points.get(x).entrySet();
    }
}
```

