solutions.content:
The idea behind this solution is once we get the input point, we loop through all the unique point we have in the map and treat them as the opsite point of the square. Then check the map to see if we can find the rest of the two points to make a square. Once we found it, we update our rest.
A small trick here is to use the hashvalue of each point as the key of our map, this could save us some space.
Add O(1)
count O(n)

```
class DetectSquares {
    private HashMap<Integer, Integer> map;
    public DetectSquares() {
        map = new HashMap<>();
    }

    public void add(int[] point) {
        int key = point[0] * 1001 + point[1];
        map.put(key, map.getOrDefault(key, 0) + 1);
    } 

    public int count(int[] point) {    
        int result = 0;
        int x = point[0];
        int y = point[1];
        for(int key : map.keySet()){
            int x1 = key / 1001;
            int y1 = key % 1001;
            if(x == x1 || y == y1 || Math.abs(x - x1) != Math.abs(y - y1)) continue;    
            int c1 = map.get(key);

            int key2 = x1 * 1001 + y;
            if(!map.containsKey(key2)) continue;
            int c2 = map.get(key2);

            int key3 = x * 1001 + y1;
            if(!map.containsKey(key3)) continue;
            int c3 = map.get(key3);

            result += c1 * c2 * c3;       
        }
        return result;
    }
}
```

