solutions.content:
The idea is to use an 2D  (1001x1001) array to represent the appearance and frequrency of the input points. 
When the count function called, try every x-axis, say if you can make a square between this x-axis and the input x. This can be easily done by caculating the length of the square, and check if you can find all the other three points.

Let's say the input is [x,y]: 
Specifally, we loop each x-axis (the array), suppose the index is  i: 
then the length of edge will be:   d = |x-i|  
Now, the problem is how to find othere 3 points.  There are two scenarios to form a squares:
**Scenario 1:**    the square is above y, which means:
   j=y+d    (suppose j the the y-axis we are looking for)
  in this scenario, the other 3 points will be (i, y+d)  (i, y) (x, y+d)
**Scenario 2:** the square is under y, which means 
   j=y-d 
  in this scenario, the other 3 points will be (i, y-d)  (i, y) (x, y-d)  

  The count can be easily counted by mulitiplying the frequency of these three points. If the frequency of this point is 0, then 0 be counted. If it is more than 1, then counted multi times. 


```
class DetectSquares {
private:
    int map[1001][1001];  // Be careful: 0 <= x, y <= 1000  intotal there are 1001 elements
public:
    DetectSquares() {
        memset(map, 0, sizeof(int)*1001*1001);
    }

    void add(vector<int> point) {
        map[point[0]][point[1]]++;
    }

    int count(vector<int> point) {
        int x = point[0], y = point[1];
        int ret = 0;

        for (int i=0; i<1001; i++)
        {
            int d = abs(x-i);
            if (d==0) continue;

            int j = y-d;
            if (j>=0)
                ret += map[i][j]*map[i][y]*map[x][j];  // count by mulitiplying the three

            j = y+d;
            if (j<=1000)
                ret += map[i][j]*map[i][y]*map[x][j];  
        }        
        return ret;
    }
};
```

