# Intuition
Following is the solution that's popular on the web. It's straight forward -> add points to a map. Then in O(n) go through all points as potential diagonals of square and check if other two vertices exist. 

BUT THE TEST CASES ARE BUGGY! 
THE FOLLOWING CODE IS WRONG AFAIK - Please correct me if I'm wrong. [The code passes all testcases but I don't think its correct].

Take the simple example of 
[[0,1], [1,2], [1,0]] and the queried point is [2,1].

This does form a square between points [0,1] and [2,1] diagonal where each size is of same length = sqrt(2) and diagonals are equal length = 2. (which is enough to prove that a quadrilateral is a square). However if you inspect the code the check we do is `(abs(dx - x) != abs(dy - y))` which doesn't check for diagnoals that are parallel to x or y axis. 




