# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The though process is as follows: when we query a point, we must first find all the pairs of points where point 1 lies on the same x as the query point and point 2 lies on the same y as the query point and the distance to both of these points from the query point is the same.

Once we have these pairs, we check if we have the required diagonal point to make an entire square. We then count all the combinations of these points that we could make a square out of since there could be duplicates.

One way to easily search for these points is to use two nested unordered_maps. One that stores the y values and associated count of all points that lie on a given x line, and another that stores the x values and associated count of all points that lie on a given y line.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Use two nested unordered_maps as described above and insert to them trivially in add().

In count(), we first grab all points that lie on the same x and all points that lie on the same y. We then loop through all the pairs of these points and check if they are the same distance from the query point.

If so, we then check how many diagonal points we have to finish off the square. We then multiple the count of each of the three points we have to go with the query point together to account for all combinations we could get from duplicates.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(N^2), where N is the number of points.
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(N)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class DetectSquares {
public:
    DetectSquares() {

    }

    void add(vector<int> point) {
        points_on_x[point[0]][point[1]]++;
        points_on_y[point[1]][point[0]]++;
    }

    int count(vector<int> point) {
        // Get all points on same x and y as square.
        unordered_map<int, int> ys = points_on_x[point[0]];
        unordered_map<int, int> xs = points_on_y[point[1]];

        // For all combinations, determine if they form a square.
        int count = 0;

        // For each y value of each point on the same x vertical
        for (const auto& y : ys) {
            // For each x value of each point on the same y horizontal
            for (const auto& x : xs) {
                // Check same dimensions and size
                if (abs(y.first - point[1]) != abs(x.first - point[0]) || abs(y.first - point[1]) == 0 || abs(x.first - point[0]) == 0) {
                    continue;
                }

                // Valid square, add as many as there are duplicate diagonal points.
                int num_diag_duplicates = points_on_x[x.first][y.first];
                count += num_diag_duplicates * x.second * y.second;
            }
        }

        return count;
    }

private:
    // Store all y values that lie on each x vertical and the count of each
    unordered_map<int, unordered_map<int,int>> points_on_x;

    // Store all x values that lie on each y horizontal and the count of each
    unordered_map<int, unordered_map<int,int>> points_on_y;
};

