# 2013. Detect Squares
C++ solutions with an approach and it's optimization.
![Screenshot 2023-01-09 173205.jpg](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/2cb1dd16-8cf8-4b4f-bbc3-f708f5fed1bd_1673265824.886406.jpeg)

## Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Because we need to store a value at first and then count some desired values by iterating through a current set of values, the use of maps comes to mind. Because we have to store a pair of values and C++ doesn't support pair<int,int> as key in unordered_maps, we'll have to use an ordered one.

## Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
The `add()` function is fairly easy. We just need to update our map with new value (which may or may not be duplicate).
### Approach: 1 - Verdict: TLE (tc. 44/54)
In the `count` function, we have to either choose a point which has the same x-value or same y-value as the given point (because the square has to be parallel to the axes).
We iterate through our map and for all the points which satisfy this aforementioned condition, we calcute `a` or the length of the side of the square.
Then we simply multiply the values of the number of occurences of each such point and it to the final sum.

Here we need to make sure that we don't use the already counted square's point again hence, we use a visited map.

#### Code:
```
class DetectSquares {
    map<pair<int,int>,int> m;
public:
    DetectSquares() {
        m.clear();
    }

    void add(vector<int> point) {
        m[{point[0],point[1]}]++;
    }

    int count(vector<int> point) {
        int sum = 0;
        map<pair<int,int>,int> vis;
        for(auto&i:m){
            if((i.first.first==point[0]||i.first.second==point[1])&&vis[{i.first.first,i.first.second}]==0){
                int a = (i.first.first==point[0]) ? abs(i.first.second-point[1]):abs(i.first.first-point[0]);
                int temp = 0;
                if(a!=0){
                    if(i.first.first==point[0]){
                        temp+=m[{i.first.first-a,i.first.second}]*m[{point[0]-a,point[1]}];
                        temp+=m[{i.first.first+a,i.first.second}]*m[{point[0]+a,point[1]}];
                        vis[{i.first.first-a,i.first.second}]++;
                        vis[{i.first.first+a,i.first.second}]++;
                        vis[{point[0]-a,point[1]}]++;
                        vis[{point[0]+a,point[1]}]++;
                    }
                    else{
                        temp+=m[{i.first.first,i.first.second-a}]*m[{point[0],point[1]-a}];
                        temp+=m[{i.first.first,i.first.second+a}]*m[{point[0],point[1]+a}];
                        vis[{i.first.first,i.first.second-a}]++;
                        vis[{i.first.first,i.first.second+a}]++;
                        vis[{point[0],point[1]-a}]++;
                        vis[{point[0],point[1]+a}]++;
                    }
                }
                sum+=temp*i.second;

            }
        }
        return sum;
    }
};

/**
 * Your DetectSquares object will be instantiated and called as such:
 * DetectSquares* obj = new DetectSquares();
 * obj->add(point);
 * int param_2 = obj->count(point);
 */
```
### Approach: 2 - Verdict: Accepted (Beats 85.76%)
The only difference in this approach and the previous one is that there is no visited map in this one. If we think smartly, we can just select the points which have either the same x or same y (in given code I've chosen x) and add them. This ensures we don't choose the same square twice as the same y one is not considered anyways. 

Here we save the `n*log(n)` insertion time and `n*log(n)` search time with visited map.

### Code
```
class DetectSquares {
    map<pair<int,int>,int> m;
public:
    DetectSquares() {
        m.clear();
    }

    void add(vector<int> point) {
        m[{point[0],point[1]}]++;
    }

    int count(vector<int> point) {
        int sum = 0;

        for(auto&i:m){
            if(i.first.first==point[0]||i.first.second==point[1]){
                int a = (i.first.first==point[0]) ? abs(i.first.second-point[1]):0;
                int temp = 0;
                if(a!=0){
                    if(i.first.first==point[0]){
                        temp+=m[{i.first.first-a,i.first.second}]*m[{point[0]-a,point[1]}];
                        temp+=m[{i.first.first+a,i.first.second}]*m[{point[0]+a,point[1]}];
                    }

                }
                sum+=temp*i.second;

            }
        }
        return sum;
    }
};

